In [79]:
all_playlists = []
next_page_token = None
In [80]:
while True:
    playlist_response = youtube.playlists().list(
        part='snippet,contentDetails',
        channelId='UCAuUUnT6oDeKwE6v1NGQxug',  # Replace with the channel ID
        maxResults=20,  # Maximum number of items per page
        pageToken=next_page_token  # None for the first request
    ).execute()

    all_playlists.extend(playlist_response['items'])

    # Check if there is a nextPageToken
    next_page_token = playlist_response.get('nextPageToken')
    if not next_page_token:
        break

        

print(f"Total playlists fetched: {len(all_playlists)}")

Get all videos details in the channel after get the playlist¶

In [84]:
import pandas as pd

def get_video_details(youtube, playlist_id):
    videos = []
    next_page_token = None

    while True:
        # Fetch the video IDs from the playlist
        playlist_items_response = youtube.playlistItems().list(
            part='contentDetails',
            playlistId=playlist_id,
            maxResults=50,
            pageToken=next_page_token
        ).execute()

        video_ids = [item['contentDetails']['videoId'] for item in playlist_items_response['items']]

        if video_ids:
            # Fetch 'snippet', 'statistics', and 'contentDetails' for the videos
            videos_response = youtube.videos().list(
                part='snippet,statistics,contentDetails',
                id=','.join(video_ids)
            ).execute()

            for video in videos_response['items']:
                video_data = {
                    'video_id': video['id'],
                    'video_url': f"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v={video['id']}",
                    'published_at': video['snippet']['publishedAt'],
                    'title': video['snippet']['title'],
                    'description': video['snippet'].get('description', 'No description'),
                    'views': video['statistics'].get('viewCount', 0),
                    'likes': video['statistics'].get('likeCount', 0),
                    'dislikes': video['statistics'].get('dislikeCount', 0),
                    'comments': video['statistics'].get('commentCount', 0),
                    'duration': video['contentDetails']['duration']
                }
                videos.append(video_data)

        next_page_token = playlist_items_response.get('nextPageToken')
        if not next_page_token:
            break

    return videos
In [85]:
# Fetching video details for all playlists
playlist_details = []

for playlist in all_playlists:
    playlist_videos = get_video_details(youtube, playlist['id'])
    for video in playlist_videos:
        video['playlist_id'] = playlist['id']
        video['playlist_title'] = playlist['snippet']['title']
        playlist_details.append(video)

# Create DataFrame from the compiled details
df_all_videos = pd.DataFrame(playlist_details)

# Show the DataFrame
df_all_videos

Data manipulation¶

Convert Youtube duration to seconds¶

In [87]:
#pip install isodate

import isodate
In [88]:
df_all_videos ['durationSecs'] = df_all_videos ['duration'].apply (lambda x: isodate.parse_duration (x))
df_all_videos ['durationSecs'] = df_all_videos ['durationSecs'].astype('timedelta64[s]')
In [89]:
# Remove "0 days" form the durationSecs column ---- 

df_all_videos['durationSecs'] = df_all_videos['durationSecs'].dt.total_seconds()

df_all_videos.sample(20)

In [294]:
# Group by playlist_title and sum the views and comments to avoid duplicate entries
grouped_playlists = df_all_videos_2.groupby('playlist_title', as_index=False).agg({
    'views': 'sum',
    'comments': 'sum','likes': 'sum'
})

# Sort the grouped data by views
grouped_playlists = grouped_playlists.sort_values(by='views', ascending=False)

# Select the top 15 playlists after grouping
top_playlists = grouped_playlists.head(15)

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Create a bar chart for views
bars_views = plt.barh(top_playlists['playlist_title'], top_playlists['views'], color='skyblue', label='Views')

# Format the numbers to display as millions
for bar in bars_views:
    value_in_millions = bar.get_width() / 1e6  # Convert to millions
    plt.text(bar.get_width() - 1e6, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, 
             f'{value_in_millions:.1f}M', va='center', ha='center', color='black')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Count (in millions)')
plt.ylabel('Playlist Title')
plt.title('Top 15 Most Popular Playlists by Total Views and Comments')

# Add a legend
plt.legend()

# Invert y-axis to have the largest on top
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()

# Display the plot
plt.show()
In [295]:
# Sort the grouped data by comments
grouped_playlists = grouped_playlists.sort_values(by='comments', ascending=False)

# Select the top 15 playlists after grouping (based on comments)
top_playlists = grouped_playlists.head(15)

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Create a bar chart for comments
bars_comments = plt.barh(top_playlists['playlist_title'], top_playlists['comments'], color='lightcoral', label='Comments')

# Format the numbers to display comments as integers
for bar in bars_comments:
    plt.text(bar.get_width() - 1e4, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, 
             f'{int(bar.get_width())}', va='center', ha='center', color='black')

# Group by playlist_title and sum the likes
grouped_playlists_by_likes = df_all_videos_2.groupby('playlist_title', as_index=False).agg({
    'likes': 'sum'  # Summing the 'likes' column to get the total likes per playlist
})

# Sort the grouped data by likes in descending order (most liked playlists first)
grouped_playlists_by_likes = grouped_playlists_by_likes.sort_values(by='likes', ascending=False)

# Select the top 15 playlists based on likes
top_playlists_by_likes = grouped_playlists_by_likes.head(15)

# Set the figure size for plotting
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Create a bar chart for likes
bars_likes = plt.barh(top_playlists_by_likes['playlist_title'], top_playlists_by_likes['likes'], color='lightgreen', label='Likes')

# Format the numbers to display as millions
for bar in bars_likes:
    value_in_millions = bar.get_width() / 1e6  # Convert to millions
    plt.text(bar.get_width() - 1e5, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, 
             f'{value_in_millions:.1f}M', va='center', ha='center', color='black')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Total Likes (in millions)')
plt.ylabel('Playlist Title')
plt.title('Top 15 Playlists by Total Likes')

# Invert y-axis to have the largest on top
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Sort the DataFrame by playlist_title and date to ensure correct time difference calculation
df_sorted_all_videos_2 = df_sorted_all_videos_2.sort_values(by=['playlist_title', 'date'])

# Calculate the difference in days between consecutive video uploads within each playlist
df_sorted_all_videos_2['time_diff'] = df_sorted_all_videos_2.groupby('playlist_title')['date'].diff().dt.days

# Group by playlist_title and calculate the average time difference for each playlist
average_period_per_playlist = df_sorted_all_videos_2.groupby('playlist_title')['time_diff'].mean().reset_index()

# Sort the playlists by the average period between uploads in ascending order (optional)
average_period_per_playlist = average_period_per_playlist.sort_values(by='time_diff', ascending=True)

# Display the average period between video uploads for each playlist
print("Average period (in days) between video uploads per playlist:")
average_period_per_playlist.head(20)

# Group by playlist_title and find the most recent upload date for each playlist

# Calculate the number of days since the last video was uploaded
most_recent_playlist['days_since_last_upload'] = (pd.Timestamp.now() - most_recent_playlist['date']).dt.days

# Extract the hour from the date column
df_sorted_all_videos_2['hour'] = df_sorted_all_videos_2['date'].dt.hour

# Group by hour and count the number of videos uploaded during each hour
upload_time_distribution = df_sorted_all_videos_2.groupby('hour').size().reset_index(name='video_count')

# Sort by the hour of the day (just to be sure it's in the right order)
upload_time_distribution = upload_time_distribution.sort_values(by='hour')

# Plot the distribution of video uploads by hour
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(upload_time_distribution['hour'], upload_time_distribution['video_count'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Hour of the Day')
plt.ylabel('Number of Videos Uploaded')
plt.title('Distribution of Video Uploads by Time of Day')
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))  # Set x-axis ticks from 0 to 23 (for each hour)
plt.grid(True)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Display the hour with the most uploads
most_common_hour = upload_time_distribution.loc[upload_time_distribution['video_count'].idxmax()]
print(f"The most common upload time is: {most_common_hour['hour']}:00 with {most_common_hour['video_count']} videos uploaded.")

# Fetch Comments and Complete Data ---

all_comments_data = []

#for _, video in df_playlist_videos.iterrows():  <--- this code alternative for the next line both working
    
for index, video in df_playlist_videos.iterrows():

    video_id = video['video_id']
    video_comments = get_comments(youtube, video_id)
    
    for comment in video_comments:
        comment_data = {
            'video_id': video_id,
            'video_url': video['video_url'],
            'video_title': video['title'],
            'views': video['views'],
            'likes': video['likes'],
            'date':video['date'],
            'time':video['time'],
            'durationSecs': video['durationSecs'],
            'comment': comment,
             #'published_at': video['published_at'], I seprat it in two columns data and time
             #  'dislikes': video['dislikes'], based on the yourube apis doesn't provied the dislike --
        }
        all_comments_data.append(comment_data)

Get word map for titles in the playlist TED-ED¶

In [187]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from collections import Counter

# Download English stopwords
nltk.download("stopwords")
english_stopwords = set(stopwords.words("english"))

# Preprocess and tokenize the text (assuming 'video_title' column contains your video titles)
all_titles = ' '.join(df_comments_TED_ED['video_title'])

# Tokenization (split by spaces)
tokens = all_titles.split()

# Remove English stopwords and perform word frequency count
filtered_tokens = [word.lower() for word in tokens if word.lower() not in english_stopwords]
word_freq = Counter(filtered_tokens)

# Create a WordCloud object with default font for English
wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, background_color='white').generate_from_frequencies(word_freq)

# Get the top 20 most common words
most_common_words = word_freq.most_common(20)

# Separate the words and their frequencies for plotting
words, frequencies = zip(*most_common_words)

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis('off')  # No axes to be shown
plt.title('Word Cloud for Video Titles', fontsize=16)
plt.show()

# Display the most common words
most_common_words = word_freq.most_common(10)
print("Most common words:")
for word, frequency in most_common_words:
    print(f"{word}: {frequency}")

    
    
# Create the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(words, frequencies, color='skyblue')  # Horizontal bar chart
plt.xlabel('Frequency')
plt.ylabel('Words')
plt.title('Top 20 Most Common Words in Video Titles')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert y-axis to show the highest frequency at the top
plt.show()

nltk.download('vader_lexicon')

In [195]:
# Initialize the VADER sentiment intensity analyzer
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

def get_sentiment(comment):
    sentiment = sid.polarity_scores(comment)
    # Classify sentiment as Positive, Neutral, or Negative based on compound score
    if sentiment['compound'] >= 0.05:
        return 'Positive'
    elif sentiment['compound'] <= -0.05:
        return 'Negative'
    else:
        return 'Neutral'
In [196]:
# Apply the sentiment function to the comments in DataFrame
df_comments_TED_ED['sentiment'] = df_comments_TED_ED['comment'].astype(str).apply(get_sentiment)

# Count the sentiment values
sentiment_counts = df_comments_TED_ED['sentiment'].value_counts()

# Plot a bar chart of the sentiment distribution
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
ax = sentiment_counts.plot(kind='bar', color=['green', 'blue', 'red'])

# Add values on top of each bar
for i in ax.patches:
    ax.text(i.get_x() + i.get_width()/2, i.get_height() + 1,   # Position the text above the bar
            str(int(i.get_height())),                          # Display the height as text
            ha='center', va='bottom')                         # Center align horizontally

plt.title('Sentiment Analysis of Arabic YouTube Comments')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment')
plt.ylabel('Number of Comments')
plt.show()
